#compdef systemd-bsod
# Documentation: source-direct extraction from upstream
# systemd/systemd src/journal/bsod.c —
#   lines 26-29 (the `arg_continuous` + `arg_tty` static
#     option-state vars)
#   lines 31-60 (help() block)
#   lines 246-278 (parse_argv() with OptionParser FOREACH_
#     OPTION_OR_RETURN + the 2 flag dispatches)
# Reference accessed: 2026-05-30 via gh api.
#
# systemd-bsod is a Linux "Blue Screen Of Death" display tool
# — filters the journal for the FIRST emergency-priority
# (LOG_EMERG = priority 0) message of the current boot and
# displays it in a full-TTY-takeover prompt with the message
# text PLUS a QR code (so the user can scan the error with a
# phone for forwarding to support).  Runs as
# `systemd-bsod.service` configured to start on
# `emergency.target`.  Newer addition (systemd v254+).
#
# Critical extraction note: bsod uses systemd's newer
# `OptionParser` + `FOREACH_OPTION_OR_RETURN` macro idiom
# (same as R218's systemd-bless-boot).  The 2 actual options
# are dispatched via the `OPTION` macro (which adds both short
# AND long form) and `OPTION_LONG` (long-only) at lines
# 262-270:
#   OPTION('c', "continuous", NULL, ...) — short+long, no arg
#   OPTION_LONG("tty", "TTY", ...)       — long-only, takes arg
# Plus the macro-injected `OPTION_COMMON_HELP` and
# `OPTION_COMMON_VERSION` auto-add `--help`/`-h`/`--version`.
#
# Critical extraction note: bsod takes NO positional arguments
# — the check at lines 273-276 rejects any leftover argv with
# the explicit error `"%s takes no argument."`.  The completion
# encodes this by not having any rest-positional spec.
#
# Critical extraction note: the journal filter chain decoded
# source-direct from acquire_first_emergency_log_message() at
# lines 62-108 — bsod ALWAYS filters by (a) current boot, (b)
# _UID=0 (root-emitted entries only), AND (c) PRIORITY=0
# (LOG_EMERG).  This is hardcoded and not configurable via
# flags; `--continuous` only controls whether the tool blocks
# waiting for new emergency messages or returns immediately if
# none found.  Documented in the `-c` description.

_arguments -s -S \
  '(-c --continuous)'{-c,--continuous}'[continuously wait for new emergency-priority messages in the journal (default: exit immediately if none)]' \
  '--tty=[path to the TTY to take over (default: detect from environment)]:tty:_files -g "/dev/(tty*|vc*|console)"' \
  '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help and exit]' \
  '--version[show package version and exit]'
